---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MetricBadge from '../../components/MetricBadge.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  lang="en"
  title="sanctuary — Global-e"
  description="A unified MCP server consolidating cross-border e-commerce support investigation into a single AI-native interface."
  pathname="/projects/global-e"
>
  <article class="container-prose pt-20 pb-16">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-3" style="color: var(--fg-soft);">
      Project 1 · Dec 2025 – Present
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-semibold mb-4" style="line-height: 1.2;">
      sanctuary — Cross-Border E-Commerce Support Automation
    </h1>
    <p class="text-base mb-8" style="color: var(--fg-soft);">
      Technical Support Engineer @ Global-e · TypeScript, MCP, MSSQL, Snowflake, Coralogix,
      Playwright
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-12 mb-4">The Problem</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Global-e operates a cross-border e-commerce platform. Technical support requires
      investigating across 10+ disconnected systems: admin portal, payment gateways (Adyen,
      Stripe, Klarna, PayPal, Worldpay), MSSQL/Snowflake databases, observability, JIRA/
      Confluence, Zendesk, email logs, and merchant Shopify stores.
    </p>
    <p>
      A single ticket investigation took <strong>2+ hours</strong> and relied on tribal knowledge
      that was difficult to transfer.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-12 mb-4">The Solution</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      I built <strong>sanctuary</strong>, a unified MCP server that consolidates the entire
      support investigation lifecycle into a single AI-native interface. I started with a
      multi-service architecture in Python and Go, then rebuilt the platform as a single
      TypeScript MCP server — reducing operational overhead while expanding capability.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-12 mb-4">Key Features</h2>

    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Unified Order Investigation</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      A single composite tool pulls the complete picture in under a minute: DB joins across 6
      pricing fields, payment transaction history, delivery timeline, refund chain, merchant
      configuration, and commercial invoice (CI) rendering — with automatic discrepancy
      detection.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Multi-PSP Payment Diagnostics</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Automated investigation across Adyen, Stripe, Klarna, PayPal, and Worldpay. The platform
      normalizes different APIs, authentication methods, and data formats into a consistent
      diagnostic view, including a 444M-row Snowflake archive for long-term payment history
      beyond MSSQL retention.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Investigation Thoroughness — 5 Stages of Self-Measurement</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      I designed a 5-stage framework that measures my own investigation quality. The system
      tracks false-positive rates, root-cause discovery frequency, and resolution-direction
      recall — with data-driven gates between stages. STAGE 1–3 deployed; STAGE 4 in active
      measurement window.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Response Quality Assurance via Codified Rules</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Before any customer-facing response is sent, an automated checker validates against
      <strong>203 feedback memory files</strong> — of which <strong
        >106 are codified into machine-checked YAML gates</strong
      > that block the violation at the tool boundary. Coverage spans prohibited terminology,
      escalation path correctness, factual accuracy, and tone calibration per recipient.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Behavioral Codification — From Mistake to Rule to Hook</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      When a mistake recurs, the system codifies it: write a feedback memory → add a YAML gate
      → install a pre-tool-use hook → block the failure mode at the tool boundary. This brought
      100+ recurring error categories down to near-zero recurrence in production.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-12 mb-6">Results</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-6 mb-8">
      <MetricBadge num="60s" label="Investigation per case (was 2hr+)" />
      <MetricBadge num="379" label="MCP tools" />
      <MetricBadge num="15,943" label="Cached tickets" />
      <MetricBadge num="203" label="Memory files (106 YAML gates)" />
    </div>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4" style="color: var(--fg-soft);">
      <li>5 PSPs unified into single diagnostic view</li>
      <li>7 services across K8s + Docker → 1 unified TypeScript server</li>
      <li>Investigation quality measurement: none → 5-stage framework with quantified gates</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-12 mb-4">What I Learned</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Consolidation beats orchestration.</strong> The earlier 7-service architecture was
      technically more impressive; the later one ships faster, debugs easier, and costs less to
      operate. The highest-value automation isn't the most complex — it's the one that removes
      the most cognitive load.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>AI agents need codified behavior, not just tools.</strong> Giving an AI agent 379
      tools is half the work. The other half is codifying <em>how</em> it should behave — what to
      verify before concluding, what to never assert without evidence, when to ask the user
      instead of guessing.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Measure your own engineering, not just the system.</strong> The Investigation
      Thoroughness framework treats my own investigation quality as a measurable artifact. Most
      engineers don't instrument themselves. The gap between "I think I'm thorough" and "I am
      measurably thorough" is the gap most worth closing.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-12">
      <a href="/codification">Read the retrospective →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
